Thank you for your comment. I think it is easy to implement a function to convert from base n to base 10, if it is not provided by the programming language. You just need to sum the powers of n, weighted by the digits of the number to convert.
Example:
"1/21/21" ==>112 in base 3 = 1 x (3^2) + 1 x (3^1) + 2 x (3^0) in base 10 = 9 + 3 + 2 = 14.
So, for C++, once you construct your an array of size m  containing the digits of a number, you just do something like:
for (i = 0, i < m, i++) {
        base_10 += digits[i] * pow(3, m-i-1)
}
/* if you store the digits from right to left, then: base_10 += digits[i] * pow(3, i) ). */

I agree that reverse translation from base 10 to base n is more difficult as you need iterative integer division, but such operation is not needed in this puzzle.
